This document outlines the environment variables required to run the Stellar Micro-Donation API. These should be defined in a .env file at the root of the project.Core API SettingsVariableDescriptionTypeDefaultRequiredNODE_ENVDeployment environment (development, staging, production).StringdevelopmentYesPORTThe port the Express server will listen on.Number3000NoAPI_KEYSecret key for internal service authentication.UUID/String-YesStellar Network ConfigurationThese variables determine which network the API interacts with and which accounts are used for transaction fees or distribution.VariableDescriptionExample / ValueRequiredSTELLAR_NETWORKThe Stellar network to use.TESTNET or PUBLICYesHORIZON_URLThe URL for the Horizon API instance.https://horizon-testnet.stellar.orgYesENCRYPTION_KEY32-character string used to encrypt/decrypt wallet seeds in the DB.a-secure-32-char-random-stringYesBASE_FEE_XLMMinimum fee in stroops for transactions.100NoSecurity Note: Never commit your .env file or any real ENCRYPTION_KEY to version control. Use the provided .env.example as a template.Database & PersistenceVariableDescriptionExampleRequiredDATABASE_URLConnection string for the primary data store.postgres://user:pass@localhost:5432/dbYesREDIS_URLConnection string for caching and recurring job queues.redis://localhost:6379YesAnalytics & Third-Party IntegrationsVariableDescriptionDefaultRequiredRECURRING_INTERVALCron syntax for the donation scheduler.0 0 * * * (Daily)NoLOG_LEVELVerbosity of system logs (error, warn, info, debug).infoNoEnvironment-Specific BehaviorDevelopment: When STELLAR_NETWORK is set to TESTNET, the system will attempt to use "Friendbot" to automatically fund newly created wallets with 10,000 test XLM.Production: When set to PUBLIC, Friendbot features are disabled, and real XLM is required for all operations. Ensure ENCRYPTION_KEY is rotated via a secure secrets manager (like AWS Secrets Manager or HashiCorp Vault).